<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO LIEN &amp; DOC SPATZ</font><br>
<tt>Sun Apr 20 17:26:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To &quot;Lien&quot; and Doc Spatz,<br>
     First, Lien, I don't think you gave Doc Spatz enough credit on his first post to you. Much of what he said about negative feelings toward Vietnamese was reporting how others felt.  I disagree with his take on multiculturalism, and will get to that later.<br><br>
     We have a sizeable number of Vietnamese in Philadelphia, mostly living in 2 neighborhoods. They have become prominent in the restaurant trade and dry cleaning. For the general public; they are just part of a more visible Asian presence, with the Koreans most visible and economically active.  Among Vietnam Veterans, some, like myself, have occasional contact with Vietnamese community and veterans' groups, and a somewhat larger group wants nothing to do with them.  The negative feelings of these people, in most cases, goes back to some individual incident(s)from the war. When we had a Vietnamese ex-POW organization over to my veterans' chapter open house and barbeque; we lost 6 members on the spot. While I was chapter president, the following year, my execuive board had no objections to my contacts with Vietnamese organizations as long as I didn't involve the rest of the chapter.  I admit this is not how things should be.<br><br>
     Am sorry that you feel the need to use an alias. There have been people on this site who have angered or frustrated me tremendously, but I don't have any bite marks so far.<br><br>
     Doc, the &quot;Little Saigon&quot; phenomenon is nothing new to this country.  Starting with the first of many &quot;Germantowns&quot; founded just northwest of Philadelphia in the 1690's to the &quot;Chinatowns&quot; in the mid-1800's to the Little Italy's that sprang up in the 1880's, immigrants formed dozens enclaves where they would feel culturally secure while at the same time starting to become a part of a new country. Most of there children or grandchildren became part of the American mainstream, but many &quot;Chinatowns&quot; and &quot;Little Italys&quot; are still viable today. Then there are cases like the Amish, who have maintained a somewhat separate existence for 250 years, still often speaking a Rhineland dialect of German among themselves and referring to outisders as &quot;English&quot;.<br><br>
     What needs to be remembered is that what is unique about our country is that it wasn't founded upon a nationality, race or creed; but upon the acceptance of the basic governing priciples embodied in the Constitution or the Declaration of Independence. I liked the comment of the historian who said he preferred the term &quot;salad&quot; to &quot;melting pot&quot;, because in the former, the flavors blended, but also remained distinct and identifiable.<br><br>
     Merging will take place over time anyway. My ancestry ranges from Native American (back in 1740 - %?)thru English arriving in the 1630's to Germans in the 1880's. Nationalities with identifiable percentages include German, Swiss, English, French and Dutch. My wife's ancetsry is Polish, lithuanian, French and Cherokee. The kids are &quot;Heinz 57&quot;, and daughter's husband is Black, Irish and Blackfoot. My cousins add Polish, Bohemian and Italian to my list. My family would not exist in most other countries. In short, Doc, don't push the panic button. We are a long way from Canada's situation over Quebec and the French language.<br>

<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


